content.description: A fun route offering a variety of sizes. Start up the wide hands corner to a mantle, then up low angle wide hands to the base of the splitter. Some fun face moves lead to mostly hand jamming (#1's & #2's) to the anchors.
content.location: To the right of Tag Team, starts in a clean, right facing corner.

content.description: Tight fingers lead over a couple blocky bulges.  Gain another varied crack that ranges from big hands to very tight hands.  Was a little sandy, but will clean up with more ascents.  Still a quality route despite the little bit of sandiness.
content.protection: 0.5 to 3.5 inch (double set is fine, you will have extra gear)
content.location:
Around the west side of the cliff; left of Solo West and right of Hair and Roses.  Plaque at bottom of route.  Start is characterized by less than vertical tight finger crack immediately right of another widening short and steep crack.

Less than 60m to ground.

content.description:
Firstly this is a left and right route combo that share anchors. Left 5.11 & right 5.10

When we lead it we started with the left side. Friction up to some fingers in the left side of the flake formation (optional tips piece to get there) then off fingers undercling/lieback (crux) to a welcome hand jam. Continue with less than vertical big hands and fist with a short OW move to gain the ledge and anchor. For the right side variation, we started up Bromance with big hands and fist then stepped over to the flake. Climb the flake with off fingers down to tips layback. Finish with a mantle to the ledge. There was some hidden cordelette just below & behind the ledge. We cleaned it and drilled a proper 2 bolt hanger. After reading a comment on the Apathy page we saw some one had mentioned they believed that what we had climbed was called "Try Me" & gave it 5,12 and the comment "hard compression climbing." We used no compression to climb either  side of the route. Not sure who or how it was originally climbed. No matter, fun climbing with a trusty anchor now!
content.protection: left: Opt. tips piece to start.Then in Camalot's .3--4.0... Right is same rack but opposite order.
content.location: This route is located not to far left from the top of the trail. Between Bromance and Apathy.

content.description: Turd Blossom is located directly to the left of Turdus Interruptus, easily identified as a clean splitter going through a roof about halfway up.  The first half is easy fists/big hands where you can utilize some face holds out to the left.  Pull through the clean roof with big hands that quickly go down to great hands as you get above the roof.  Continue up the splitter hand crack, which slowly goes to a few moves of tight hands to gain the ledge.  This thing was pretty fun!
content.protection:
(BD camalots) #1, 2 x #2, 3-4 #3, 2-3 #4

2 bolts and webbing at the top
content.location: Directly left of Turdus Interruptus

content.description: A good friend route. Climbs a shallow right facing corner with feet!
content.protection:
1-4 friend w extra 1.5

tat n biners for anchor
content.location: between solo west and lean green.

content.description:
Climb thin hands in a shallow right facing corner.

Traverse right briefly on crimps in a horizontal crack (with gear).

Climb a multi-crack system through varied sizes to a ledge.

Ascend a couple ledges to anchors potentially saving a 0.4" piece for the last moves.
content.location:
A minute left of Hand Solo and just a bit left of the Duo.  Around the corner and left of "Mine."

Start marked by shallow right facing thin hands crack to horizontal traverse right to gain another crack.

Less than 60m to ground.

Apparently a route called the Gnash(?) is located just left, and climbs a wide crack to the same anchors.

climbs.name: The Takers
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2011

content.description: Climb a hand crack flake inside a chimney that narrows to less than tips.  Pull a small roof to exit the chimney and climb a poddy flake up a slab to the chains.
content.protection: 0.5"-3.0".  A green BD TCU is nice right below the roof.
content.location: Far left side of Selfish Wall, ~10 minutes walk left from Hand Solo.

content.description: A mostly mellow finger crack in a corner with lots of face features. Crux comes near the top when the feet go away. Watch the loose rock before the anchor.
content.protection: Small gear, .3's to .5's, .75, and a gold camalot for the finish.
content.location: About 200 feet right of Hand Solo, at a shallow right facing corner. The anchor for this route and the Unnamed 5.10 are close together.

content.description: This route climbs a right facing corner that is essentialy all offwidth.  Start with easy offwidth up to a good stance on a blocky face feature.  Continue up steep, overhung offwidth to fists/tight fists.  Pull out of the overhanging fists into a flared 8" pod (crux) and easy wide hands get you to the anchor.
content.protection: Sizes in camalots: 2 each #3,4 and 5.  A # 3.5 and #4.0 friend might be good alternatives.
content.location: 30 feet  left of MMM on the far left side of the buttress.

content.description: An awkward and powerful start through the green camalot section leads to tight hands in a corner which quickly goes to good hands. A small section of cups leads to a rest and final section of slabby thin hands. Get through the first 15 feet and it's excellent 5.10 to the top.
content.protection: (Camalots) A couple .75's, a #2 Friend, 4 #1 Camalots, 3 #2's, 1 #3 Friend, 1 #3.
content.location: Right of Selfishness but before Hair and Roses. Obvious clean, shallow left facing corner in dark rock.

content.description: Beautiful thin hands/layback corner. Some thin climbing at the start, then a nice rest before the crux, which is a 20 foot section of ringlocks/lb. Gorgeous, black varnished rock.
content.protection: From blue alien to #1 camalot with extra 0.5 and 0.75 camalots.  Good 2 bolt anchor.
content.location: About 5 minutes to the right of Hand Solo.  Look for the striking left facing corner.

content.description:
If it were only longer it would certainly get 5 stars!

A right facing corner with tips to fingers and some cool face features (don't get tunnel vision here) to gain the ledge where the 2 bolt anchor is located.
content.protection: Blue Metolius - grey Alien
content.location: Far-ish right side of the crag passing the classic Soloeast. Between Self Maid & Semi Selfish.

content.description: A right facing corner with a fair amount of face features on its right wall. I gave this a "PG" rating only because in certain sections the gear placements are shallow. It starts by going past some suspect looking small blocks (however seemed quite secure to me) followed by some off fingers. Eventually the crack becomes fingers, thin fingers and a seam. Near the top is some awkward stemming/chimney-ing passing a lead bolt which brings you to a mantle finish and a 2 bolt anchor.
content.protection: set of Aliens Black through Gray. A single 0.5 & .75 Camalot. 1 quick draw
content.location: ​​​​On the right side of the buttress, 3 or 4 corner systems right of Solo East.

content.description: Right facing flake with hands and offwidth
content.protection: Some thin hand/hand size cams, a couple fours and a five or two(new sizes). It's short so it's easy to scope. Bolt anchors.
content.location: Route is 30 feet to the left of Lean and Green.

content.description:
The short obtuse corner with sharp edged crack right of the ooze, and left of/shares anchor with OW to the right.

Thin jams or begs to be laybacked.

green c4, maybe a purple, or burn it on TR after leading a little masochistic.
content.protection: 0.75 camalots, maybe a 0.5

content.description: Start up the corner with off fingers/tight hands. Move left to the main crack system and climb with tight hands. After a good rest stance push through the steep crux first with off fingers that turns to fingers. Exit right at the lip to a comfortable belay stance.
content.protection: 0.3 - 1.0 camelot's (heaviest on 0.5's)
content.location: Located on the far right side of the crag. Between I & I and Semi Selfish. Roughly 2 corner systems right of Solo East. It is the right facing corner with a significant patch of white calcite at its base.

content.description:
Not the best looking rock, but climbs well and is fun.  Also one of the longer routes on this wall of shorter climbs.

Climb double cracks (3-3.5") and then the fingery crack above.  Clip a bolt that protects a section where the crack pinches down to nothing (crux).  Climb past another bolt on easier terrain eventually arriving at a stretch of very easy off-width skirted by using the right wall.

Crux may end up feeling harder for those with bigger fingers, and vice versa.
content.protection: A double set from 0.5 to 3.5", with big gear being optional because the wide section is easy and can also be protected in a separate crack with 4" gear.
content.location:
Left side of cliff, several minutes from Hand Solo.  Left of Hair and Roses.  Right facing dihedral with two bolts halfway up - fairly obvious.

Less than 60m to ground.

content.description:
A left-leaning crack in the back of a fairly low-angle right-facing corner.  A large calcite sheet marks the left wall about 20 feet up.

Anchors are on the left side.  (The wide crack to the left might also work off these anchors).
content.protection:
Fingers at the start, then mostly green and red camalots (yikes), some purples.

Biners are on the anchor bolts.
content.location: Around the south-facing side of the crag, not too far around the corner from Hand Solo.  I don't have the book, so I'm not sure where this lies in the sequence of named climbs.  A plaque marks the base.

climbs.name: MMM (Misanthropic Mustache Man)
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2011

content.description:
Climb thin hands in a left facing corner over a small roof and continue up thin hands to a rightwards jog in the crack and a another mini-roof.  More thin hands leads to a large roof and the crack steps right again.  Pull the roof and climb past a hollow flake to  more thin hands and  the chains.

Expect a little soft rock but it's better than it looks from the ground.
content.protection: Heavy on 1.5"-2.0". Chain anchor with biners.
content.location: Far left side of Selfish Wall, ~10 minutes walk left from Hand Solo.

content.description: A nicely varied corner that suffers from some soft rock and slightly awkward climbing at times, but it's a decent warm up. The crack at the top is flaring and while the holds are good you need very small cams to fit securely where it pinches down.
content.protection: Single set from .2 Camalot to a new 5. Might want doubles of .2 to .5.
content.location: Obvious dihedral between Apathy and the Ooze.

content.description: start up the 5.10- finger crack.  About 10 feet up reach left and clip a bolt with a runner.  Comit to dictate face moves trending up and left to second bolt. Gain a stance place 2 green c3's and fire up the arête slapping compression problem.  Step left and fire up fingers to hands up to the anchor.
content.protection:
Quick draws a runner and tiny gear through hands.  Probably a single set from fingers to hands and a few extra micro peices.

(Note the crux can not be aided as the crack goes away for for the boulder problem)
content.location: A few routes left of solo east.  Look for the dark varnished rock with two black bolts.

content.description: Starts in a short steep right facing corner off of a ledge. Scrambles left to another right facing corner. Start up this with a bouldery move then move left to a finger flake. Climb/stem your way up the flake to its end and a two bolt anchor.
content.protection: In Camalot sizes 0.3- 2.0
content.location: Walking right from the top of the trail, you will have a mandatory step down off of a rock. This route is located just before the step down as well as the route "Mean Black Dog."

content.description:
This is a new route and it still has some suspect rock. Two chunks big enough to seriously injure or kill a belayer came off the day I climbed it, so heads up. It may become a fun, moderate addition to the crag once it cleans up.

Start in a wide flare that quickly pinches down to a more manageable sized crack. Climb easier, somewhat broken terrain to the anchor below a small roof. The is a plaque at the base showing the route name, but no grade was given.
content.protection: Cams to BD #3.
content.location: Near the far left side of Selfish Wall. The next climb right of the Selfishness offwidth flake.

content.description: Off-fingers in a small right facing corner to straight-in fingers through a bulge.  Excellent stone.
content.protection: Heavy on 0.75 and 0.5 camalots.
content.location: West face, couple minutes left from Hand Solo.

content.description: Infidel climbs the right side of a large pillar just right of Dilated Cervix.  Climb all sizes of hands and two small offwidth pods to reach the top of the pillar.
content.protection: Thin to wide hands, 1 five inch piece.
content.location: This route is located on the far left side of Selfish Wall, ~15 minutes walk from Hand Solo.

climbs.name: Id
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2011

content.description: Climb steep splitter thin hands off the ground to good stemming out left.  The crack widens from hands to fists and trends left into a small right facing corner with interesting face features.  Pull a corner change and the crack narrows from hands to fingers with an offwidth pod at the top.  Could be a bit harder for shorter folks.
content.protection: 0.75"-4.0".  Chain anchor, shares anchors with Ego.
content.location: Far left side of Selfish Wall, ~10 minutes walk left from Hand Solo.

content.description: A right facing dihedral with big hands and fists, first a bulge that reminds you of incredible hand crack then over a jutting block with good hand in the back up to an awkward sandy finish with good chicken wing move and small pockets on the right wall. Anchors are hard to see from the ground on a big ledge on the right.
content.protection: 1x #2 Camamlot, 3x #3camalot, 2x#3.5camalot, 1x#4camalot for the top,
content.location: just to the right of Solo East

content.description: This unlikely line begins at the base of a ramping, left facing corner with fists.  The easy corner quickly steepens and seams out as it arcs to the left.  Fun face climbing on the arete leads to the top of a small pillar.  From the pillar reach out left and a clip a bolt.  Jump to the positive rail and mantle to the base of a splitter.  Climb tips/fingers up the spiltter for ~20 feet where the climbing eases and follow thin hands/hands to the top.
content.protection: 0.2-3.0 BD, one QD, extra thin fingers.
content.location: This route is on the far left side of Selfish Wall, ~15 minutes walk from Hand Solo. It shares an anchor with Infidel.

content.description: Full value climbing - tight chimney to fingers to hands to offwidth and back to sweet fingers & thin hands. The top has the finger locks and foot holds you wish Solo East had. Ends at Solo East anchor.
content.protection: Thin fingers to bd5 (or 6 if you want). Multiples in the small sizes. Ends at Solo East anchors.
content.location: Immediately left of Solo East.

content.description: Splitter hands with lots of face features.
content.protection: Couple hand size pieces.
content.location: Obvious short splitter where approach trail meets crag.

climbs.name: Hair and Roses
climbs.fa: Michael Covington, Charlotte Fox, Angela Donini - Fall 2009

content.description:
A variable crack in the back of an open book.  Wide to start, then goes to tips, then an incut hand crack.

From the top of the crack, head right up the ramp to find the anchor bolts.  NOTE: this upper ramp has been sloughing off a fair amount of loose rock, so try to clear the shooting gallery of pedestrians before approaching or using the anchor.

Reportedly, the FA only used one cam, the rest was done on nuts and hexes.
content.protection: Almost-sub-tips (0 or 00 C3?) to gold camalots.  Anchor bolts off to the right (which are not visible from the base).
content.location:
On the south side of the crag, about 40 feet around the corner left of Turdus Interruptus.

A new plaque marks the route's base (the original one disappeared).

content.description: It is in a cave of sorts. Jam & stem your way up to the Caves end.
content.protection: Single rack from 0.4-4.0 will be more than enough
content.location: The furthest right route on the wall and approximately 5 minute walk from I & I

content.description: This is an interesting route that would be really hard if it wasn't for the wide crack to its right that you are able to stem off of (A Little More Masochism).
content.protection: Thin hands to tight fingers.
content.location: Just left of A Little More Masochism.  You can scramble up to the top of the starting ledge on the left.

content.description: A great pitch with some sicko roof climbing! Climb tha right-facin corner wit a funky-roof loomin above. Climb all up in tha low pod n' fire up ta tha roof, plug a piece n' cook up some delicate but strenuous moves till it widens up wit betta holds. Easy climbin ta tha anchor. Shiiit, dis aint no joke. Shares anchors wit Lean n' Green.
content.protection: .3, Multiple .5s (Red aliens and Orange TCU's fit real nice), #2, I placed a 3 all up in tha lip, you could plug something bigger at the roof but thats the tough spot so dont waste yer time. + Alpine draws!
content.location: Just right of Lean n' green, R facin corner dat goes all up in a thin-wide roof.

climbs.name: Fuck You and Your Selfie Stick

content.description: Fun, adventurous climb with mostly hands/tight hands in Slot-Machine-style slots, and some brief squeeze/OW transitions to keep things interesting.
content.protection: In BD, several (3-5ish) #1-2, maybe doubles #3-4, and a #5 is optional but useful at some of the pods. Lots of slings.  A 60m rope might be too short for TR, but I will update when this is known.
content.location: The route starts with a fingers move to a sandy pod and then 20 feet of sharp varnished splitter hands. In case there is any confusion there is a fresh-looking plaque at the base.

climbs.name: Ego
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2011

content.description: Climb a thin hands splitter past a pod to a flake that covers the crack. Continue up the left leaning thin hands flake to a ledge and the chains.
content.protection: 2.0"-2.5".  Chain anchor, shares anchors with Id.
content.location: Far left side of Selfish Wall, ~10 minutes walk left from Hand Solo.  Furthest left route on the wall.

content.description: Next thin crack system right of Tag Team. Starts with thin pro, pull the low crux, then cruise up the slab layback. Head right toward the hand crack, then back left up a hand/fist crack to the anchors on Tag Team. Single rack, small cams - bd4.
content.protection: Single rack, small cams - bd4.  Tag team anchor
content.location: See the pictures. 20 ft right of Tag Team.

content.description:
Original start climbs wide flake to gain ledge (did not climb this).  Next climb from ledge up hand crack to anchors below roof. (5.10)

Direct start climbs short 1.5" crack to a short finger crack of all finger sizes.  Hand jam in the middle.  Probably 10+ or 11- ??
content.protection:
Left start: wide gear.

Direct start: varied finger sizes, including one 0.4" piece

Upper corner: mix of 2.25" to 3" gear; mostly gold camalots
content.location:
Just a very short walk left of Hand Solo.  Left facing corner begins off a ledge with two separate starts to choose from.

Less than 60m to ground.

climbs.name: Dilated Cervix
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2011

content.description: This route begins in a finger splitter inside a large cave created by a huge flake leaning against the wall.  Climb splitter fingers and chimney until you don't fit anymore and then exit the chimney on hand jams to a nice ledge below the splitter.  Climb thin hands to a pod and then ring locks to another pod and chains.
content.protection: 0.75"-2.0".  Extra 1.5"  Chain anchor.
content.location: Far left side of Selfish wall, ~10 minute walk left of Hand Solo.

content.description: This is a new line and it's still a bit dirty and crumbly in places so beware. Fight up the offwidth, possibly with the help of some faceholds that rarely seem to be in very useful positions. Once you reach the ledge it's still not over. Climb another shorter and easier offwidth crack to the anchor. Save a #5 or #6 for this section. The plaque identifying the climb gives it a 9+ rating but the #6 crux section midway seemed harder than that compared to other offwidths I've climbed at the Creek.
content.protection: Mostly big gear (#4 - #6 camalots). A #6 may be optional if you have a couple #5s.
content.location: Look for an offwidth crack in a shallow right-facing dihedral. It's one of the first climbs you come to after hanging a left at the top of the approach trail and immediately right of the Bromance offwidth. The two climbs share an anchor.

content.description:
P1: 5.6 Start on a pedestal with fists and a number 5 to gain the ledge. Stem, jam, squeeze with ok pro deep and left until the next ledge. Squeeze, jam, pull your way pass the loose chockstones. FA placed a cam on either side, a #4 Big bro should work here, or some nuts to keep it tight. Reach to a pocket on the left to help pull the ledge. Moderately "ok" *GEAR ANCHOR* with #2 and 2x#3's deep in the back to the right

P2: Down climb gully left with some wide stems once you reach the edge climb double cracks to right to gain access to a ledge, squirm your way down a squeeze chimney. Watch your first step on to the next ledge, rock is shakey. Use the anchors for Bromance/ Cousin Luv'n to repel to the ground.

Warning Loose Rock:

FA did their best to clean it up but still is a little chossy so make sure you're wearing a helmet.

If anyone wants to clean it up a little more and toss up some anchors that would be sweet. Looks like there is a possible 1-2 pitches that could be added to the right. I might be back for this if no one gets to it.
content.protection: 0.3 - 5, nuts or a #4 big bro if you don't wanna double nut a loose chockstone
content.location: Just 15 feet left of the left variation of Duo.

climbs.name: Bromance
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2010

content.description: Climb wide hands over a small roof to easy offwidth.
content.protection: 0.75, 3.0, 4.0 and 5.0 camalots. The last 15' is too wide for a #6 but the climbing is easy. Chain anchor.
content.location: Left of Hand Solo ~2 minutes.

content.description: A fun easily protected ramp with an easy set of finger locks and horns, with pockets on the left wall. Also an Arete on the left which comes into reach further up, the ramp steepens before a pod that requires a short move to clip the bolt
content.protection: All small stuff starts with purple.5 and green.75, then some reds and a #4 old style camalot to protect the base of the pod really make it comfortable for beginners.
content.location: Right of the unnamed 5.10 right facing corner behind the tree and to the left of Solo East.

climbs.name: Apathy
climbs.fa: Alex Garhart and Toni Walters, April 2010

content.description: Begin in a thin open book corner right of the obvious bolt.  Work your way up to a couple of small holds and a stance where you can reach left and clip a bolt.  Make a delicate leftwards traverse to a good flake and mantle to another flake where you can reach a less than tips splitter on the left that takes 00 and 0 C3's.  Make a fun bouldery move out of a pod to gain a small horizontal flake and a good stance below a small right facing corner.  Climb tips to perfect fingers up the corner to a fingers/off-fingers splitter that goes to the chains.
content.protection: Small tcu's, tips, fingers and off-fingers, 1 QD.  Chain anchor.
content.location: First route left of Bromance.

content.description: Right of the ooze, Offwidth. #4 to 5 to 6 to 5 camalots. Short but good OW practice
content.protection: #4, (2)#5, (2)#6, #4big bro and then #3 big bro to protect the move onto the top. Can easily march up your #5s and #6s. Hand stacks until your knee fits (good rest), then armbar and chickenwings with footstacks to your hearts content. You can walk 4-5-6-5 fine or take extras.

content.description: The wider crack just left of The Ooze.  Good climb for people wanting to practice jamming hand stacks.
content.protection:
#4 camalots & a #3.

2 bolt anchor
